      Adsorption Kinetics and Size Exclusion Properties of Probe Molecules for the Selective Porosity in a Carbon Molecular Sieve Used for Air Separation
      Reid, C. R.; Thomas, K. M.
      Journal of Physical Chemistry B (2001), 105 (43), 10619-10629CODEN: JPCBFK; ISSN:1089-5647. (American Chemical Society)
      The adsorption characteristics of planar (ethylene, benzene, and pyridine) and tetrahedral (methane, chloromethane, dichloromethane, chloroform, and carbon tetrachloride) mols. on a carbon mol. sieve used for air sepn. (CMS A) were studied over a range of temps. as a function of pressure, to study the selective porosity. The size-exclusion characteristics of planar and tetrahedral mols. indicate that the selective porosity behaves as though it has spherical-shaped structural characteristics and, therefore, two min. dimensions need to be considered in relation to size exclusion. The partial exclusion of the probe mol. adsorptives from the microporous structure for sizes >360 pm allowed the selective and nonselective microporosity and the meso/macroporosity to be quantified. Adsorption kinetics obey a linear-driving-force mass transfer, combined barrier resistance/diffusion, or Fickian kinetic models depending on the adsorptive and exptl. conditions. Comparison of the results with previous studies of the adsorption of linear and spherical mols. on CMS A show that a decrease in the adsorption rate const. of ∼4 orders of magnitude was obsd. for an increase in mol. size over the range ∼290-420 pm. The activation energies and preexponential factors for the adsorption kinetics and the isosteric heats of adsorption are discussed in terms of the structural characteristics of the adsorptives and the adsorption mechanism.

      Characterization of Microporous Carbons Using Adsorption at Near Ambient Temperatures
      Jagiello, Jacek; Bandosz, Teresa J.; Schwarz, James A.
      Langmuir (1996), 12 (11), 2837-2842CODEN: LANGD5; ISSN:0743-7463. (American Chemical Society)
      The adsorption isotherms of CF4 and SF6 measured at various temps. near ambient are used to obtain information about micropore structure of 2 com. carbons. This information is extd. from the comprehensive anal. of the data on 3 levels of assumptions. Heats of adsorption allow for qual. comparison of adsorption energetics between different carbons. Finally the micropore size distributions are calcd. from the adsorption energy distributions assuming that the adsorption energy of mols. confined in micropores is detd. by their sizes and geometry. No assumptions are made about the anal. form of the distribution. Effects of model assumptions (e.g., gas-solid interaction parameters or the pore wall thickness) on the calcd. micropore size distributions are discussed. The present results are compared with the results of an independent chromatog. method based on the exclusion effect to obtain better insight on pore size distribution and geometry of actual carbons.

      The adsorption of mol. hydrogen in the Prussian blue analog Cu3[Co(CN)6]2 was studied using high-resoln. neutron powder diffraction and neutron vibrational spectroscopy. Rietveld structural refinement of the neutron data for hydrogen loadings of 1, 2, and ∼2.3 H2/Cu showed that the hydrogen was absorbed at 2 sites within the structure. The most prominent adsorption site, located at the (1/4, 1/4, 1/4) crystallog. site, was an interstitial location within the structure. The 2nd adsorption site was assocd. with exposed Cu2+ ion coordination sites that result from the presence of [Co(CN)6]3- vacancies within the structure of the material. The rotational-vibrational d. of states of the adsorbed hydrogen was probed using neutron vibrational spectroscopy and showed a range of local binding potentials for the adsorbed hydrogen.

      Quantum Sieving in Carbon Nanotubes and Zeolites
      Wang, Qinyu; Challa, Sivakumar R.; Sholl, David S.; Johnson, J. Karl
      Physical Review Letters (1999), 82 (5), 956-959CODEN: PRLTAO; ISSN:0031-9007. (American Physical Society)
      Fluids adsorbed in microporous materials can exhibit quantum sieving, where heavy isotopes are preferentially adsorbed over light isotopes. The authors present the first detailed predictions of quantum sieving based on realistic models of microporous materials. Carbon nanotubes, and the interstices of nanotube bundles, can act as highly effective quantum sieves for hydrogen isotopes. Quantum sieving of He and Ne in the zeolite AlPO4- 22 is also discussed.

      Adsorption and separation of hydrogen isotopes in carbon nanotubes: Multicomponent grand canonical Monte Carlo simulations
      Challa, Sivakumar R.; Sholl, David S.; Johnson, J. Karl
      Journal of Chemical Physics (2002), 116 (2), 814-824CODEN: JCPSA6; ISSN:0021-9606. (American Institute of Physics)
      Adsorption isotherms of H isotopes from mol. simulations in C nanotubes and interstices are presented. The adsorption of pure isotopes follows Henry's law up to moderate coverages. A modified path integral grand canonical Monte Carlo (PI-GCMC) technique for mixt. adsorption is presented and applied to adsorption of isotope mixts. in C nanotubes. Adsorption isotherms of H2-T2 mixts. in nanotubes and interstices are detd. at 20°K and 77°K. Selectivities for T over H are calcd. over a range of pressures. Selectivity in the nanotubes and interstices increases with pressure until the nanotube is satd. Comparison of simulation results with predictions based on ideal adsorbed soln. theory (IAST) shows good agreement up to moderate loadings. At higher loadings, selectivities detd. from multicomponent simulations remain roughly const., whereas IAST predicts continued increase in selectivities. Isotherms for H2-D2 and the selectivities of D2 over H2 are detd. for adsorption in (10,10) nanotubes and in the interstitial channels of closed (10,10) nanotubes.

      Adsorption of Gases in Metal Organic Materials: Comparison of Simulations and Experiments
      Garberoglio, Giovanni; Skoulidas, Anastasios I.; Johnson, J. Karl
      Journal of Physical Chemistry B (2005), 109 (27), 13094-13103CODEN: JPCBFK; ISSN:1520-6106. (American Chemical Society)
      Mol. simulations using std. force fields have been carried out to model the adsorption of various light gases on a no. of different metal org. framework-type materials. The results have been compared with the available exptl. data to test the validity of the model potentials. We observe good agreement between simulations and expts. for a no. of different cases and very poor agreement in other cases. Possible reasons for the discrepancy in simulated and measured isotherms are discussed. We predict hydrogen adsorption isotherms at 77 and 298 K in a no. of different metal org. framework materials. The importance of quantum diffraction effects and framework charges on the adsorption of hydrogen at 77 K is discussed. Our calcns. indicate that at room temp. none of the materials that we have tested is able to meet the requirements for on-board hydrogen storage for fuel cell vehicles. We have calcd. the vol. available in a given sorbent at a specified adsorption energy (d. of states). We discuss how this d. of states can be used to assess the effectiveness of a sorbent material for hydrogen storage.

      Quantum Effects on Adsorption and Diffusion of Hydrogen and Deuterium in Microporous Materials
      Kumar, A. V. Anil; Jobic, Herve; Bhatia, Suresh K.
      Journal of Physical Chemistry B (2006), 110 (33), 16666-16671CODEN: JPCBFK; ISSN:1520-6106. (American Chemical Society)
      Monte Carlo and mol. dynamics simulations and neutron scattering expts. are used to study the adsorption and diffusion of hydrogen and deuterium in zeolite Rho in the temp. range of 30-150 K. In the mol. simulations, quantum effects are incorporated via the Feynman-Hibbs variational approach. We suggest a new set of potential parameters for hydrogen, which can be used when Feynman-Hibbs variational approach is used for quantum corrections. The dynamic properties obtained from mol. dynamics simulations are in excellent agreement with the exptl. results and show significant quantum effects on the transport at very low temp. The mol. dynamics simulation results show that the quantum effect is very sensitive to pore dimensions and under suitable conditions can lead to a reverse kinetic mol. sieving with deuterium diffusing faster than hydrogen.

      Adsorption equilibriums of hydrogen, deuterium, and their mixtures
      Basmadjian, I. D.
      Canadian Journal of Chemistry (1960), 38 (), 141-8CODEN: CJCHAG; ISSN:0008-4042.
      Adsorption isotherms of H2 and D2 were measured over the range 75-90°K. and at 760 mm. Hg on charcoal, SiO2 gel, and mol. sieves (Linde, type 4A, 5A, and 13X). D2 was adsorbed to a greater extent than H2 in all cases, and its isosteric heat of adsorption exceeded that of H2 by 50 to 300 cal./mole. The binary adsorption isotherms were detd. on the above adsorbants at 75° and 90°K. and at a total pressure of 750 and 200 mm. Hg. The mixts. were analyzed by thermal cond. The binary sepn. factors were const. over the entire concn. range but varied from 1.25 on charcoal to 2.54 on type-4A mol. sieves. The results suggest also that the variation in adsorption is due to the chem. compn. of the adsorbent rather than to pore size, surface area, or origin of the material.

        Adsorption Dynamics of Gases and Vapors on the Nanoporous Metal Organic Framework Material Ni2(4,4'-Bipyridine)3(NO3)4: Guest Modification of Host Sorption Behavior
        Fletcher, Ashleigh J.; Cussen, Edmund J.; Prior, Timothy J.; Rosseinsky, Matthew J.; Kepert, Cameron J.; Thomas, K. Mark
        Journal of the American Chemical Society (2001), 123 (41), 10001-10011CODEN: JACSAT; ISSN:0002-7863. (American Chemical Society)
        This study combines measurements of the thermodn. and kinetics of guest sorption with powder x-ray diffraction measurements of the nanoporous metal org. framework adsorbent (host) at different adsorptive (guest) loadings. The adsorption characteristics of nitrogen, Ar, CO2, nitrous oxide and EtOH and MeOH vapors on Ni2(4,4'-bipyridine)3(NO3)4 were studied over a range of temps. as a function of pressure. Isotherm steps were obsd. for both CO2 and nitrous oxide adsorption at ∼10-20% of the total pore vol. and at ∼70% of total pore vol. for MeOH adsorption. The adsorption kinetics obey a linear driving force (LDF) mass transfer model for adsorption at low surface coverage. At high surface coverage, both MeOH and EtOH adsorption follow a combined barrier resistance/diffusion model. The rates of adsorption in the region of both the CO2 and MeOH isotherm steps were significantly slower than those obsd. either before or after the step. X-ray diffraction studies at various MeOH loadings showed that the host structure disordered initially but underwent a structural change in the region of the isotherm step. These isotherm steps are ascribed to discrete structural changes in the host adsorbent that are induced by adsorption on different sites. Isotherm steps were not obsd. for EtOH adsorption, which followed a Langmuir isotherm. Previous x-ray crystallog. studies showed that all the sites are equiv. for EtOH adsorption on Ni2(4,4'-bipyridine)3(NO3)4, with the host structure undergoing a scissoring motion and the space group remaining unchanged during adsorption. The activation energies and preexponential factors for MeOH and EtOH adsorption were calcd. for each pressure increment at which the linear driving force model was obeyed. There was a good correlation between activation energy and ln(preexponential factor), indicating a compensation effect. The results are discussed in terms of reversible adsorbate/adsorbent (guest/host) structural changes and interactions and the adsorption mechanism. The paper contains the 1st evidence of specific interactions between guests and functional groups leading to structural change in flexible porous coordination polymer frameworks.

        Adsorption of Gases and Vapors on Nanoporous Ni2(4,4'-Bipyridine)3(NO3)4 Metal-Organic Framework Materials Templated with Methanol and Ethanol: Structural Effects in Adsorption Kinetics
        Fletcher, Ashleigh J.; Cussen, Edmund J.; Bradshaw, Darren; Rosseinsky, Matthew J.; Thomas, K. Mark
        Journal of the American Chemical Society (2004), 126 (31), 9750-9759CODEN: JACSAT; ISSN:0002-7863. (American Chemical Society)
        Desolvation of Ni2(4,4'-bipyridine)3(NO3)4·2CH3OH and Ni2(4,4'-bipyridine)3(NO3)4·2C2H5OH give flexible metal-org. porous structures M and E, resp., which have the same stoichiometry, but subtly different structures. This study combines measurements of the thermodn. and kinetics of carbon dioxide, methanol, and ethanol sorption on adsorbents M and E over a range of temps. with adsorbent structural characterization at different adsorbate (guest) loadings. The adsorption kinetics for methanol and ethanol adsorption on porous structure E obey a linear driving force (LDF) mass transfer model for adsorption at low surface coverage. The corresponding adsorption kinetics for porous structure M follow a double exponential (DE) model, which is consistent with two different barriers for diffusion through the windows and along the pores in the structure. The former is a high-energy barrier due to the opening of the windows in the structure, required to allow adsorption to occur, while the latter is a lower-energy barrier for diffusion in the pore cavities. X-ray diffraction studies at various methanol and ethanol loadings showed that the host porous structures E and M underwent different scissoring motions, leading to an increase in unit cell vol. with the space group remaining unchanged during adsorption. The results are discussed in terms of reversible adsorbate/adsorbent (host/guest) structural changes and the adsorption mechanism involving hydrogen-bonding interactions with sp. surface sites for methanol and ethanol adsorption in relation to pore size and extent of filling. This paper contains the first evidence for individual kinetic barriers to diffusion through windows and pore cavities in flexible porous coordination polymer frameworks.

        Influence of Connectivity and Porosity on Ligand-Based Luminescence in Zinc Metal-Organic Frameworks
        Bauer, Christina A.; Timofeeva, Tatiana V.; Settersten, Thomas B.; Patterson, Brian D.; Liu, Vincent H.; Simmons, Blake A.; Allendorf, Mark D.
        Journal of the American Chemical Society (2007), 129 (22), 7136-7144CODEN: JACSAT; ISSN:0002-7863. (American Chemical Society)
        Applications of metal-org. frameworks (MOFs) require close correlation between their structure and function. The authors describe the prepn. and characterization of two Zn MOFs based on a flexible and emissive linker mol., stilbene, which retains its luminescence within these solid materials. Reaction of trans-4,4'-stilbenedicarboxylic acid (H2L) and zinc nitrate in DMF yielded a dense 2-dimensional network, Zn3L3(DMF)2 (1), featuring Zn in both octahedral and tetrahedral coordination environments connected by trans-stilbene links. The emission spectrum of 2 depends on the nature of the incorporated solvent mols., suggesting use of this or related materials in sensor applications.

        Vapochromism and Its Structural Basis in a Luminescent Pt(II) Terpyridine-Nicotinamide Complex
        Wadas, Thaddeus J.; Wang, Quan-Ming; Kim, Yong-Joo; Flaschenreim, Christine; Blanton, Thomas N.; Eisenberg, Richard

        A novel Pt(II) terpyridine complex that has a nicotinamide moiety linked to the terpyridyl ligand has been synthesized in good yield and studied structurally and spectroscopically. The complex, [Pt(Nttpy)Cl](PF6)2 where Nttpy = 4'-(p-nicotinamide-N-methylphenyl)-2,2':6',2''-terpyridine, is obsd. to be brightly luminescent in the solid state at room temp. and at 77 K. The crystal and mol. structures of the orange and red forms, detd. by single-crystal X-ray diffraction on the same single crystal, were found to be equiv. in the mol. sense and only modestly different in terms of packing. In both forms, the cationic Pt(II) complexes possess distorted square planar geometries. Anal. of the orange form's crystal packing reveals the presence of solvent mols. in lattice voids, Pt···Pt sepns. averaging 3.75 Å and a zigzag arrangement between nearest neighbor Pt atoms, whereas the red form is devoid of solvent within the crystal lattice and contains complexes stacked with a nearly linear arrangement of Pt(II) ions having an av. distance of 3.33 Å. On the basis of the crystallog. data, it is evident that sorption of methanol vapor induces a change in intermol. contacts and Pt···Pt interactions in going from red to orange. Disruption of the d8-d8 metallophilic interactions consequently alters the emitting state from 3[(d)σ*-π*(terpyridine)] that is formally a metal-metal-to-ligand charge transfer (MMLCT) state in the red form to one in which the HOMO corresponds to a more localized Pt(d) orbital in the red form (3MLCT).

        Highly controlled acetylene accommodation in a metal-organic microporous material
        Matsuda, Ryotaro; Kitaura, Ryo; Kitagawa, Susumu; Kubota, Yoshiki; Belosludov, Rodion V.; Kobayashi, Tatsuo C.; Sakamoto, Hirotoshi; Chiba, Takashi; Takata, Masaki; Kawazoe, Yoshiyuki; Mita, Yoshimi

        Metal-org. microporous materials (MOMs) have attracted wide scientific attention owing to their unusual structure and properties, as well as com. interest due to their potential applications in storage, sepn. and heterogeneous catalysis. One of the advantages of MOMs compared to other microporous materials, such as activated carbons, is their ability to exhibit a variety of pore surface properties such as hydrophilicity and chirality, as a result of the controlled incorporation of org. functional groups into the pore walls. This capability means that the pore surfaces of MOMs could be designed to adsorb specific mols.; but few design strategies for the adsorption of small mols. have been established so far. Here we report high levels of selective sorption of acetylene mols. as compared to a very similar mol., carbon dioxide, onto the functionalized surface of a MOM. The acetylene mols. are held at a periodic distance from one another by hydrogen bonding between two non-coordinated oxygen atoms in the nanoscale pore wall of the MOM and the two hydrogen atoms of the acetylene mol. This permits the stable storage of acetylene at a d. 200 times the safe compression limit of free acetylene at room temp.

The overall crystal packing efficiency of the coordination frameworks, which ultimately dets. their soly., also plays an important role in the anion crystn. selectivity under thermodn. equilibration.

        A homochiral metal-organic porous material for enantioselective separation and catalysis

        Organoplatinum crystals for gas-triggered switches
        Albrecht, Martin; Lutz, Martin; Spek, Anthony L.; van Koten, Gerard
        Nature (London) (2000), 406 (6799), 970-974CODEN: NATUAS; ISSN:0028-0836. (Nature Publishing Group)
        Considerable effort is being devoted to the fabrication of nanoscale devices. Mol. machines, motors and switches were made, generally operating in soln., but for most device applications (such as electronics and opto-electronics), a maximal degree of order and regularity is required. Cryst. materials would be excellent systems for these purposes, as crystals comprise a vast no. of self-assembled mols., with a perfectly ordered three-dimensional structure. In nonporous crystals, however, the mols. are densely packed and any change in them (due, for example, to a reaction) is likely to destroy the crystal and its properties. Here the authors report the controlled and fully reversible cryst.-state reaction of gaseous SO2 with nonporous cryst. materials consisting of organoplatinum mols. This process, including repetitive expansion-redn. sequences (on gas uptake and release) of the crystal lattice, modifies the structures of these mols. without affecting their crystallinity. The process is based on the incorporation of SO2 into the colorless crystals and its subsequent liberation from the orange adducts by reversible bond formation and cleavage. The authors therefore expect that these cryst. materials will find applications for gas storage devices and as opto-electronic switches.

        Lefebvre, Julie; Batchelor, Raymond J.; Leznoff, Daniel B.

The solvent mols. adsorbed by Cu[Au(CN)2]2 bind to the CuII centers, thereby altering the visible spectrum assocd. with the CuII chromophores and the no. and frequency of the νCN as well. The network-stabilizing Au-Au interactions and the flexible coordination sphere of CuII probably facilitate reversible solvent exchange at room temp.

        We report the synthesis of zeolite-like carbon materials that exhibit well-resolved powder x-ray diffraction patterns and very high surface area. The hydrogen uptake capacity obsd. for the zeolite-like carbon materials is among the highest ever reported for carbon (activated carbon, mesoporous carbon, carbon nanotubes) or any other (MOFs, zeolites) porous material.

        Kubas, Gregory J.
        Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America (2007), 104 (17), 6901-6907CODEN: PNASA6; ISSN:0027-8424. (National Academy of Sciences)
        A review of the binding of a dihydrogen mol. (H2) to a transition metal center in an organometallic complex as a major discovery is presented because it changed the way chemists think about the reactivity of mols. with chem. inert strong bonds such as H-H and C-H. H2 complexes are of increased relevance for H2 prodn. and storage in the H economy of the future.

        Characterization of H2 Binding Sites in Prototypical Metal-Organic Frameworks by Inelastic Neutron Scattering
        Rowsell, Jesse L. C.; Eckert, Juergen; Yaghi, Omar M.
        Journal of the American Chemical Society (2005), 127 (42), 14904-14910CODEN: JACSAT; ISSN:0002-7863. (American Chemical Society)

        Kinetic Isotope Effect for H2 and D2 Quantum Molecular Sieving in Adsorption/Desorption on Porous Carbon Materials
        Zhao, Xuebo; Villar-Rodil, Silvia; Fletcher, Ashleigh J.; Thomas, K. Mark
        Journal of Physical Chemistry B (2006), 110 (20), 9947-9955CODEN: JPCBFK; ISSN:1520-6106. (American Chemical Society)
        Adsorption and desorption of H2 and D2 from porous C materials, such as activated C at 77 K, are usually fully reversible with very rapid adsorption/desorption kinetics. The adsorption and desorption of H2 and D2 at 77 K on a C mol. sieve (Takeda 3A), where the kinetic selectivity was incorporated by C deposition, and a C, where the pore structure was modified by thermal annealing to give similar pore structure characteristics to the C mol. sieve substrate, were studied. The D2 adsorption and desorption kinetics were significantly faster (up to ×1.9) than the corresponding H2 kinetics for specific pressure increments/decrements. This represents the 1st exptl. observation of kinetic isotope quantum mol. sieving in porous materials due to the larger zero-point energy for the lighter H2, resulting in slower adsorption/desorption kinetics compared with the heavier D2. The results are discussed in terms of the adsorption mechanism.

        Molecular Dimensions for Adsorptives
        Webster, Charles Edwin; Drago, Russell S.; Zerner, Michael C.
        Journal of the American Chemical Society (1998), 120 (22), 5509-5516CODEN: JACSAT; ISSN:0002-7863. (American Chemical Society)
        Pore vols., accessible surface areas, and the thermodn. of adsorption are essential in the understanding of solid surface characteristics fundamental to catalyst and adsorbent screening and selection. The recently developed Multiple Equil. Anal. (MEA) provides a thorough characterization of the adsorption process. Mol. properties such as mol. vols. and projected mol. areas are needed in order to convert moles adsorbed to surface vols. and probe dependent, accessible surface areas. These mol. quantities are also needed in conventional methods for detg. areas and pore vols. Generally, these mol. properties have been estd. from bulk properties, but many assumptions are required. As a result, different literature values are employed for these essential mol. properties. In this article, mol. structures for various conformers of many mols. are calcd. using ZINDO. Mol. vols. and excluded mol. areas are detd. from these structures and tabulated for a variety of mols. Mol. dimensions of mols. are another important consideration needed to understand mol. exclusion as well as size and shape selectivity. Mol. dimensions along the symmetry axes are tabulated as well as the two smallest min. dimensions of each mol. Examples are presented to illustrate the use of these quantities in shape and size selectivity, mol. exclusion, diffusion, and adsorbent selection.

        Compensation Effect for the Kinetics of Adsorption/Desorption of Gases/Vapors on Microporous Carbon Materials
        Fletcher, Ashleigh J.; Thomas, K. Mark
        Langmuir (2000), 16 (15), 6253-6266CODEN: LANGD5; ISSN:0743-7463. (American Chemical Society)
        Preliminary studies of adsorption kinetics on activated carbon provided some tentative evidence for a possible compensation effect where the activation energies and ln(preexponential factors) obtained from the Arrhenius equation obey a linear correlation. However, a detailed anal. was not carried out. The adsorption characteristics of a series of n-alc. vapors on the activated carbon BAX950 were investigated over the relative pressure range p/po = 0-0.97, for temps. in the range 288-318 K. These data, in combination with our previous results for water, n-octane, and n-nonane adsorption provide a comprehensive adsorption kinetic study on an active carbon covering a full range of adsorptives with varying hydrophilic/hydrophobic character to establish the general validity, applicability, and mechanism of the compensation effect. The results are discussed with ref. to the pore structure and the adsorption mechanism. Detailed comparisons show that the compensation effect is a general phenomenon for adsorption and desorption on microporous carbons and may extend further to other porous systems.

        There is considerable interest in hydrogen adsorption on carbon nanotubes and porous carbons as a method of storage for transport and related energy applications. The max. amts. of hydrogen adsorbed correlated with the micropore vol. obtained from extrapolation of the Dubinin-Radushkevich equation for carbon dioxide adsorption. Functional groups have a small detrimental effect on hydrogen adsorption, and this is related to decreased adsorbate-adsorbent and increased adsorbate-adsorbate interactions.

        Quantum Effects on Hydrogen Isotope Adsorption on Single-Wall Carbon Nanohorns
        Tanaka, Hideki; Kanoh, Hirofumi; Yudasaka, Masako; Iijima, Sumio; Kaneko, Katsumi
        Journal of the American Chemical Society (2005), 127 (20), 7511-7516CODEN: JACSAT; ISSN:0002-7863. (American Chemical Society)
        H2 and D2 adsorption on single-wall carbon nanohorns (SWNHs) have been measured at 77 K, and the exptl. data were compared with grand canonical Monte Carlo simulations for adsorption of these hydrogen isotopes on a model SWNH. Quantum effects were included in the simulations through the Feynman-Hibbs effective potential. The simulation predictions show good agreement with the exptl. results and suggest that the hydrogen isotope adsorption at 77 K can be successfully explained with the use of the effective potential. According to the simulations, the hydrogen isotopes are preferentially adsorbed in the cone part of the SWNH with a strong potential field, and quantum effects cause the d. of adsorbed H2 inside the SWNH to be 8-26% smaller than that of D2. The difference between H2 and D2 adsorption increases as pressure decreases because the quantum spreading of H2, which is wider than that of D2, is fairly effective at the narrow conical part of the SWNH model. These facts indicate that quantum effects on hydrogen adsorption depend on pore structures and are very important even at 77 K.

        Adsorption of Gases and Vapors on Carbon Molecular Sieves
        O'koye, I. P.; Benham, M.; Thomas, K. M.
        Langmuir (1997), 13 (15), 4054-4059CODEN: LANGD5; ISSN:0743-7463. (American Chemical Society)
        The adsorption phenomena of oxygen and nitrogen on a carbon mol. sieve were studied above the crit. temp. of the adsorptives as a function of pressure in order to understand further the mechanism of air sepn. The uptake of both gases studied was virtually linear at low equil. pressures, in agreement with Henry's law, but deviation occurred at higher pressures. The adsorption kinetics were studied with different amts. of preadsorbed gas for changes in pressure of 11 kPa and partial pressure in helium of ∼10 kPa. The gas adsorption kinetics obey a linear driving force mass transfer model. The ratios of the rate consts. (kO2/kN2) for each pressure increment were 35-43 for pure gases and 21-27 for gas/helium mixts., and these ratios clearly demonstrate the mol. sieving characteristics. The presence of water vapor is detrimental to the operation of carbon mol. sieves. The adsorption and desorption characteristics of water vapor with different amts. of preadsorbed water were studied for comparison with oxygen and nitrogen adsorption over the pressure range 0-1.8 kPa for pressure steps of 0.1 kPa. The results are discussed in terms of the mechanism of gas sepn. using carbon mol. sieves.

        Adsorption of Gases on Carbon Molecular Sieves Used for Air Separation. Spherical Adsorptives as Probes for Kinetic Selectivity
        Reid, C. R.; O'koye, I. P.; Thomas, K. M.
        Langmuir (1998), 14 (9), 2415-2425CODEN: LANGD5; ISSN:0743-7463. (American Chemical Society)
        The adsorption of oxygen, nitrogen, and a series of noble gases (neon, argon, and krypton) on a carbon mol. sieve were studied over a range of temps. above the crit. temp. of the adsorptives as a function of pressure in order to understand further the mechanism of air sepn. The noble gases were used as probes for the selective porosity in the carbon mol. sieve. The uptakes of all gases studied were virtually linear at low equil. pressures in agreement with Henry's law, but deviation occurred at higher pressures. The isosteric enthalpies of adsorption were calcd. from the variation in the Henry's law const. with temp. The adsorption kinetics were studied with different amts. of preadsorbed gas for pressure increments in the range 1-100 kPa. The adsorption kinetics obey a linear driving force mass transfer model for oxygen, nitrogen, argon, and krypton for the exptl. conditions studied. The adsorption kinetics for neon deviate from this model, and the data fit a kinetic model which combines diffusion and barrier resistance characteristics. The ratios of the rate consts. (k(O2)/k(N2)) for each pressure increment in the pressure range 0-9 kPa over the temp. range 303-313 K were typically 25, and this clearly demonstrates the mol. sieving characteristics. The activation energies for the adsorption process were in the order krypton > argon > nitrogen > oxygen ∼ neon. The results are discussed in terms of the mechanism of gas sepn. using carbon mol. sieves.

        Adsorption of Gases on a Carbon Molecular Sieve Used for Air Separation: Linear Adsorptives as Probes for Kinetic Selectivity
        Reid, C. R.; Thomas, K. M.
        Langmuir (1999), 15 (9), 3206-3218CODEN: LANGD5; ISSN:0743-7463. (American Chemical Society)
        The adsorption of oxygen, nitrogen, and a series of gases/vapors with linear structures (carbon monoxide, carbon dioxide, nitrous oxide, acetylene and carbon disulfide) on a carbon mol. sieve typical of the materials used for air sepn. were studied over a range of temps. as a function of pressure in order to understand further the mechanism of air sepn. The ratios of the rate consts. (kO2/kN2) were typically 25 for the carbon mol. sieve used thereby demonstrating the mol. sieving characteristics. The adsorption kinetics obey a linear driving force (LDF) mass transfer model for most of the gases and exptl. conditions studied. However there were deviations from the LDF model for carbon dioxide and nitrous oxide. In the case of the former, the kinetic models ranged from LDF through a combined barrier resistance/diffusion model to Fickian diffusion depending on the exptl. conditions. The adsorption rate consts. increase exponentially with increasing surface coverage for the mols. which follow the LDF model. The barrier resistance kinetic consts. derived from the combined barrier resistance/diffusion model also have an exponential dependence on surface coverage. The results are discussed in terms of the mechanism of gas sepn. using carbon mol. sieves.

        Adsorption Kinetics and Size Exclusion Properties of Probe Molecules for the Selective Porosity in a Carbon Molecular Sieve Used for Air Separation
        Reid, C. R.; Thomas, K. M.
        Journal of Physical Chemistry B (2001), 105 (43), 10619-10629CODEN: JPCBFK; ISSN:1089-5647. (American Chemical Society)
        The adsorption characteristics of planar (ethylene, benzene, and pyridine) and tetrahedral (methane, chloromethane, dichloromethane, chloroform, and carbon tetrachloride) mols. on a carbon mol. sieve used for air sepn.         Characterization of Microporous Carbons Using Adsorption at Near Ambient Temperatures
        Jagiello, Jacek; Bandosz, Teresa J.; Schwarz, James A.
        Langmuir (1996), 12 (11), 2837-2842CODEN: LANGD5; ISSN:0743-7463. (American Chemical Society)
        The adsorption isotherms of CF4 and SF6 measured at various temps. near ambient are used to obtain information about micropore structure of 2 com. carbons. This information is extd. from the comprehensive anal. of the data on 3 levels of assumptions. Heats of adsorption allow for qual. comparison of adsorption energetics between different carbons. No assumptions are made about the anal. form of the distribution. Effects of model assumptions (e.g., gas-solid interaction parameters or the pore wall thickness) on the calcd. micropore size distributions are discussed. The present results are compared with the results of an independent chromatog. method based on the exclusion effect to obtain better insight on pore size distribution and geometry of actual carbons.

        Quantum Sieving in Carbon Nanotubes and Zeolites
        Wang, Qinyu; Challa, Sivakumar R.; Sholl, David S.; Johnson, J. Karl
        Physical Review Letters (1999), 82 (5), 956-959CODEN: PRLTAO; ISSN:0031-9007. (American Physical Society)
        Fluids adsorbed in microporous materials can exhibit quantum sieving, where heavy isotopes are preferentially adsorbed over light isotopes. The authors present the first detailed predictions of quantum sieving based on realistic models of microporous materials. Carbon nanotubes, and the interstices of nanotube bundles, can act as highly effective quantum sieves for hydrogen isotopes. Quantum sieving of He and Ne in the zeolite AlPO4- 22 is also discussed.

      112. 112
        Challa, S. R., Sholl, D. S., and Johnson, J. K. J. Chem. Phys. 2002, 116, 814– 824
        [Crossref], [CAS], Google Scholar
        112
        Adsorption and separation of hydrogen isotopes in carbon nanotubes: Multicomponent grand canonical Monte Carlo simulations
        Challa, Sivakumar R.; Sholl, David S.; Johnson, J. Karl
        Journal of Chemical Physics (2002), 116 (2), 814-824CODEN: JCPSA6; ISSN:0021-9606. (American Institute of Physics)
        Adsorption isotherms of H isotopes from mol. simulations in C nanotubes and interstices are presented. The adsorption of pure isotopes follows Henry's law up to moderate coverages. A modified path integral grand canonical Monte Carlo (PI-GCMC) technique for mixt. adsorption is presented and applied to adsorption of isotope mixts. in C nanotubes. Adsorption isotherms of H2-T2 mixts. in nanotubes and interstices are detd. at 20°K and 77°K. Selectivities for T over H are calcd. over a range of pressures. Selectivity in the nanotubes and interstices increases with pressure until the nanotube is satd. Comparison of simulation results with predictions based on ideal adsorbed soln. theory (IAST) shows good agreement up to moderate loadings. At higher loadings, selectivities detd. from multicomponent simulations remain roughly const., whereas IAST predicts continued increase in selectivities. Isotherms for H2-D2 and the selectivities of D2 over H2 are detd. for adsorption in (10,10) nanotubes and in the interstitial channels of closed (10,10) nanotubes.
        >> More from SciFinder ®
        https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&resolution=options&coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BD38XjvFalug%253D%253D&md5=b86729ca724f2ef5ce3315d36cc0257f
      113. 113
        Garberoglio, G., Skoulidas, A. I., and Johnson, J. K. J. Phys. Chem. B 2005, 109, 13094– 13103
        [ACS Full Text ], [CAS], Google Scholar
        113
        Adsorption of Gases in Metal Organic Materials: Comparison of Simulations and Experiments
        Garberoglio, Giovanni; Skoulidas, Anastasios I.; Johnson, J. Karl
        Journal of Physical Chemistry B (2005), 109 (27), 13094-13103CODEN: JPCBFK; ISSN:1520-6106. (American Chemical Society)
        Mol. simulations using std. force fields have been carried out to model the adsorption of various light gases on a no. of different metal org. framework-type materials. The results have been compared with the available exptl. data to test the validity of the model potentials. We observe good agreement between simulations and expts. for a no. of different cases and very poor agreement in other cases. Possible reasons for the discrepancy in simulated and measured isotherms are discussed. We predict hydrogen adsorption isotherms at 77 and 298 K in a no. of different metal org. framework materials. The importance of quantum diffraction effects and framework charges on the adsorption of hydrogen at 77 K is discussed. Our calcns. indicate that at room temp. none of the materials that we have tested is able to meet the requirements for on-board hydrogen storage for fuel cell vehicles. We have calcd. the vol. available in a given sorbent at a specified adsorption energy (d. of states). We discuss how this d. of states can be used to assess the effectiveness of a sorbent material for hydrogen storage.
        >> More from SciFinder ®
        https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&resolution=options&coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BD2MXltlyrsbs%253D&md5=73b98fa9a5d8e6e0d289cf2a14b490e0
      114. 114
        Kumar, A. V. A., Jobic, H., and Bhatia, S. K. J. Phys. Chem. B 2006, 110, 16666– 16671
        [ACS Full Text ], [CAS], Google Scholar
        114
        Quantum Effects on Adsorption and Diffusion of Hydrogen and Deuterium in Microporous Materials
        Kumar, A. V. Anil; Jobic, Herve; Bhatia, Suresh K.
        Journal of Physical Chemistry B (2006), 110 (33), 16666-16671CODEN: JPCBFK; ISSN:1520-6106. (American Chemical Society)
        Monte Carlo and mol. dynamics simulations and neutron scattering expts. are used to study the adsorption and diffusion of hydrogen and deuterium in zeolite Rho in the temp. range of 30-150 K. In the mol. simulations, quantum effects are incorporated via the Feynman-Hibbs variational approach. We suggest a new set of potential parameters for hydrogen, which can be used when Feynman-Hibbs variational approach is used for quantum corrections. The dynamic properties obtained from mol. dynamics simulations are in excellent agreement with the exptl. results and show significant quantum effects on the transport at very low temp. The mol. dynamics simulation results show that the quantum effect is very sensitive to pore dimensions and under suitable conditions can lead to a reverse kinetic mol. sieving with deuterium diffusing faster than hydrogen.

        A Metal-Organic Framework with Entatic Metal Centers Exhibiting High Gas Adsorption Affinity
        Ma, Shengqian; Zhou, Hong-Cai
        Journal of the American Chemical Society (2006), 128 (36), 11734-11735CODEN: JACSAT; ISSN:0002-7863. (American Chemical Society)
        A metal-org. framework, H2[Co4O(TATB)8/3] (PCN-9, H3TATB = 4,4',4''-s-triazine-2,4,6-triyltribenzoic acid), contg. entatic metal centers, was synthesized and crystallog. characterized, and its gas adsorption was studied. The H2 and CH4 adsorption enthalpies of PCN-9 are among the highest reported thus far.

      117. 117
        Basmadjian, I. D. Can. J. Chem. 1960, 38, 141– 148
        [Crossref], [CAS], Google Scholar
        117
        Adsorption equilibriums of hydrogen, deuterium, and their mixtures
        Basmadjian, I. D.
        Canadian Journal of Chemistry (1960), 38 (), 141-8CODEN: CJCHAG; ISSN:0008-4042.
        Adsorption isotherms of H2 and D2 were measured over the range 75-90°K. and at 760 mm. Hg on charcoal, SiO2 gel, and mol. sieves (Linde, type 4A, 5A, and 13X). D2 was adsorbed to a greater extent than H2 in all cases, and its isosteric heat of adsorption exceeded that of H2 by 50 to 300 cal./mole. The binary adsorption isotherms were detd. on the above adsorbants at 75° and 90°K. and at a total pressure of 750 and 200 mm. Hg. The mixts. were analyzed by thermal cond. The binary sepn. factors were const. over the entire concn. range but varied from 1.25 on charcoal to 2.54 on type-4A mol. sieves. The results suggest also that the variation in adsorption is due to the chem. compn. of the adsorbent rather than to pore size, surface area, or origin of the material.
